    label "3"
    text " dream interpretation sits at the intersection of neuroscience, psychoanalysis, anthropology, and personal narrative"
  ]
  node [
    id 4
    label "4"
    text " There&#8217;s no singular answer to what dreams mean, but multiple overlapping frameworks help us understand why we dream and what those experiences reflect"
  ]
  node [
    id 5
    label "5"
    text " From a neurobiological perspective, dreaming occurs mostly during REM sleep, when the brain&#8217;s visual and emotional centers are highly active"
  ]
  node [
    id 6
    label "6"
    text " The prefrontal cortex, associated with logic and impulse control, is relatively quiet"
  ]
  node [
    id 7
    label "7"
    text " That&#8217;s why dreams often feel vivid and bizarre, but we accept them while they&#8217;re happening"
  ]
  node [
    id 8
    label "8"
    text " One model suggests that dreams help process emotional experiences and consolidate memory"
  ]
  node [
    id 9
    label "9"
    text " Another, the threat simulation theory, argues that dreaming evolved to mentally rehearse dangerous scenarios&#8212;like being chased or falling&#8212;as a kind of cognitive preparedness"
  ]
  node [
    id 10
    label "10"
    text " Freud viewed dreams as expressions of unconscious desires, while Jung saw them as messages from a collective unconscious, filled with archetypes and symbolic meaning"
  ]
  node [
    id 11
    label "11"
    text " In modern psychotherapy, especially Jungian and Gestalt approaches, clients might be asked to 'become' different elements of a dream and explore their emotional relevance"
  ]
  node [
    id 12
    label "12"
    text " Culturally, dream meanings vary"
  ]
  node [
    id 13
    label "13"
    text " In some Indigenous traditions, dreams are seen as guidance from ancestors or spirit worlds"
  ]
  node [
    id 14
    label "14"
    text " In others, they&#8217;re omens or warnings"
  ]
  node [
    id 15
    label "15"
    text " That cultural layer adds another dimension&#8212;dreams are shaped not just by the brain, but by belief systems"
  ]
  node [
    id 16
    label "16"
    text " Ultimately, dreams are deeply subjective"
  ]
  node [
    id 17
    label "17"
    text " Some people recall them nightly and assign great meaning; others forget them entirely"
  ]
  node [
    id 18
    label "18"
    text " Studying dreams offers insight into how the mind works when the usual filters are off"
  ]
  node [
    id 19
    label "19"
    text " Whether or not we 'decode' them, they reveal something about our inner lives"
